Here's a typical `MauiProgram.cs` setup:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

namespace MyMauiApp;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder
            .UseMauiApp<App>()
            .ConfigureFonts(fonts =>
            {
                fonts.AddFont("OpenSans-Regular.ttf", "OpenSansRegular");
            });

        // Services
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

#if DEBUG
        builder.Logging.AddDebug();
#endif

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes?**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reusing one instance avoids socket exhaustion. One connection pool for the app. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`, holds no per-user state — one instance serves everyone and can maintain a shared cache. |
| `MainViewModel` | **Transient** | Fresh state every time the page is created. Avoids stale data when navigating back. |
| `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Same reasoning — each navigation to the detail page should start clean. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | New page instance per navigation, matching the transient ViewModels they depend on. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateless or shared-state services (HTTP clients, caches, config).
- **Transient** — pages and ViewModels so each navigation gets a fresh instance.
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET), but useful if you create your own `IServiceScope` for a workflow.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **transient** into a **singleton** — the transient effectively becomes a singleton too (captive dependency). The DI graph above avoids this: singletons only depend on other singletons.
